ined Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\ndocs/milestones.md:153:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \ndocs/milestones.md:154: It should add distributed, morphology-bound intraneuronal state and nothing else that can trivially explain the result.\ndocs/milestones.md:156:**What observable will convince you that the surface model matters?**  \ndocs/milestones.md:171:* **Weak:** the surface model shows propagation or spread that the point model cannot show by construction  \ndocs/milestones.md:172:* **Moderate:** the surface model changes a shared readout such as null-direction suppression, latency, or DSI  \ndocs/milestones.md:173:* **Strong:** the shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuffled  \ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \ndocs/milestones.md:217:  * propagation delays  \ndocs/milestones.md:266:* **surface-simulated:** T4a and T5a  \ndocs/milestones.md:269:* **readout stop point:** T4a/T5a axon terminals in lobula plate layer 1\ndocs/milestones.md:284:* T4a and T5a in surface mode  \ndocs/milestones.md:321:* promote **L1/L2/L3 point models** if the upstream delay abstraction becomes the main criticism  \ndocs/milestones.md:345:* both of you can explain why this boundary is sufficient for the first morphology-sensitive test  \ndocs/milestones.md:372:  - point-simulated  \ndocs/milestones.md:373:  - skeleton-simulated  \ndocs/milestones.md:374:  - surface-simulated\ndocs/milestones.md:386:- flagging missing metadata needed for later coupling/mode